<subSubSection box="[199,1024,570,597]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1437,282,885]" box="[199,1024,570,597]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,570,596]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Host plant</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[338,448,571,597]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Ledeb." authorityName="Ledeb." box="[459,739,570,597]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Agrimonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[459,654,570,597]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Agrimonia pilosa</emphasis>
Ledeb.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Lee, H. - S." box="[753,1013,570,597]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="209 - 212" refId="ref78457" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Lee, H. - S. (2011) Host plants and larvae of two leaf-rolling sawfly species of the genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) in Korea. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 17, 209 - 212." type="journal article" year="2011">Shinohara &amp; Lee 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="64" pageNumber="65" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1437,282,885]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,606,632]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species has much in common with 
<taxonomicName authority="Shinohara, 1985" authorityName="Shinohara" authorityYear="1985" box="[763,1088,606,633]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="decorata">
<emphasis box="[763,897,606,633]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">O. decorata</emphasis>
Shinohara, 1985
</taxonomicName>
, from 
<collectingCountry box="[1159,1226,607,633]" name="Japan" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Japan</collectingCountry>
, in adult and larval morphology and host plant (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[470,666,642,668]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="644 - 653" refId="ref76313" refString="Shinohara, A. (1987 b) Systematic studies on the genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) of the Far East I. Kontyu, Tokyo, 55, 644 - 653." type="journal article" year="1987">Shinohara 1987b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Lee, H. - S." box="[678,939,642,669]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="209 - 212" refId="ref78457" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Lee, H. - S. (2011) Host plants and larvae of two leaf-rolling sawfly species of the genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) in Korea. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 17, 209 - 212." type="journal article" year="2011">Shinohara &amp; Lee 2011</bibRefCitation>
). In our molecular analyses, the two species were also quite close, diverging by a minimum of 1.1% in COI and 0.3% in NaK. The two species formed a clade with 100% UFBoot support in both COI and NaK analyses (
<figureCitation box="[821,922,714,740]" captionStart="FIGURE 139" captionStartId="228.[151,250,1667,1691]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,190,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-26@228.[151,1436,181,1643]" captionTargetPageId="228" captionText="FIGURE 139. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda, part 2." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Figs 139</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[933,979,714,741]" captionStart="FIGURE 153" captionStartId="240.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,186,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@240.[172,1415,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="240" captionText="FIGURE 153. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">153</figureCitation>
). However, we treat them as distinct species, because the differences between them (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[647,841,750,776]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="644 - 653" refId="ref76313" refString="Shinohara, A. (1987 b) Systematic studies on the genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) of the Far East I. Kontyu, Tokyo, 55, 644 - 653." type="journal article" year="1987">Shinohara 1987b</bibRefCitation>
) are small but quite constant.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1437,282,885]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
The newly acquired female specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[682,757,786,812]" name="Russia" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Russia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[771,851,786,812]" captionStart="FIGURE 38" captionStartId="127.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-19@127.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="FIGURE 38. Onycholyda nigroclypeata, female, Russia – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) sawsheath laterally, (h) claw." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
) has extensively orange-marked temples and vertex, but is otherwise not distinguishable from other specimens (
<figureCitation box="[820,902,822,848]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="126.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-26@126.[151,1436,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="126" captionText="FIGURE 37. Onycholyda nigroclypeata, female, Korea – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) sawsheath laterally, (g) antenna." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[926,1124,822,848]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="644 - 653" refId="ref76313" refString="Shinohara, A. (1987 b) Systematic studies on the genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) of the Far East I. Kontyu, Tokyo, 55, 644 - 653." type="journal article" year="1987">Shinohara 1987b</bibRefCitation>
). The pale coloration of the head of this specimen is asymmetrical suggesting its aberrant nature (
<figureCitation box="[929,1026,858,884]" captionStart="FIGURE 38" captionStartId="127.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-19@127.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="127" captionText="FIGURE 38. Onycholyda nigroclypeata, female, Russia – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) sawsheath laterally, (h) claw." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 38e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
